metadata.name: O B S C V R V M #356
metadata.description:
‚ÄúFelix, qui potuit rerum cognoscere causas‚Äù
Virgil, from Georgica, 29 BCE

The miracle of the appropriateness of the language of mathematics for the formulation of the laws of physics is a wonderful gift which we neither understand nor deserve. OBSCVRVM, meaning ‚Äúdarkness‚Äù in Latin, takes this profound insight from physicist Eugene Wigner and explores it through a series of code generated spatial compositions. This collection redefines basic concepts of distance and time, with elements in the scene seemingly evolving at different spatial and temporal scales. Its universe exists on the ambiguous boundary between the cosmic and subatomic, forgoing color in place of structure, articulated through a single light source and myriad of shadows it casts on the intricate lattice geometries.

Every token is a spatial composition consisting of a frame, a central lattice and a background, layered in space like theater scenography. Many frames are narrow and take a form of a portal, some take up the whole space in between, and some are missing altogether. Background features a star field with celestial objects like stars, planets, moons, eclipses and comets. The universe of OBSCVRVM is highly ordered, with lattice-like structures imprinted in star fields that span thousands of light years. You might find shattered lattices close to ancient celestial objects like meteor fields, novas, quasars and space-time raptures. In this universe time flows unevenly, and it might take eons for destructive forces to completely disintegrate the lattice and take it to its ultimate state ‚Äì heath death. Lattices themselves are formed through iterative subdivision rules from basic Platonic primitives. Special types of derived primitives called stations also appear, their origin still a mystery. Occasionally, a central lattice is missing from the composition, leaving the portal to frame a seemingly empty region of space. With over 250 calls to a random function within the code, the number of spatial configurations this generative system can produce is astoundingly large, although the collection explores only a small subset of them. 

Virgil‚Äôs quote from the beginning translates to: ‚ÄúFortunate them, who were able to know the causes of things‚Äù. We know little about the origin of these lattices, but through their intricate geometries, OBSCVRVM takes you on a journey to explore deep space and time and ponder over our own place in them.

LLP üññ

__________

OBSCVRVM collection is written in JavaScript using THREE.js library for displaying instantiated 3D geometry. Generation of lattices is done using our own, open-source mesh subdivision module, which includes a custom mesh class. 

Key controls:

a : jump light angle
f : cycle light framerate
t : cycle light tick
i : info
g : start / stop gif capture
b : white / black background
1 ‚Äì 5 : image capture 1-5x resolution 

Token looks best in live mode and 100% browser zoom. Change pixel density by changing your browser's zoom level (50% zoom doubles the pixels etc.) Tested on multiple browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge), devices (desktop, mobile) and operating systems (Windows, iOS). For best viewing experience, we recommend Chrome on desktop with a newer generation GPU card and enabled hardware acceleration. Due to recursive nature of geometry generation, some tokens might take much more time to generate. Please make sure the token works on your device before minting.

We were greatly inspired by Jacek Markusiewicz‚Äôs ‚Äúadrift‚Äù, lunarean's ‚ÄúHeat Death‚Äù, and Monotau‚Äôs ‚ÄúCradle‚Äù collections on fxhash, both by their approach to code as well as aesthetic synthesis of elements of their work. They motivated us to leave our code open (unminified and unobfuscated), available on public repositories (GitHub), and well documented through writing and talks so they can serve as inspiration to others. We see our support for open generative tools as a mission every generative artist should partake in. 

Created in 2022 by {protocell:labs}. You can find us on Twitter - @LukaPiskorec @00000Kane00000

metadata.name: Sugar Skulls #111
metadata.description:
Sugar Skulls are confectionery creations traditionally made with cane sugar and decorated as part of the Mexican celebration of Day of the Dead, or D√≠a de Muertos and All Souls Day on the first and second days of November when the dead are remembered and honored. 

So, why are they showing up here at Christmas? Well, why not?!? Christmas is a great time to enjoy a free, sweet treat while remembering those loved ones we‚Äôve spent past Christmases with who are no longer with us.  

While most images here are of traditional sugar skulls, some lucky ones are accessorized with Santa Claus or Elf hats. 

Minting is free for as long as the project remains open. The creator may elect to close the project at any time. There is absolutely no utility promised or implied beyond the nifty artwork itself. Created for Christmas 2022.

Merry Christmas!

metadata.name: Divine Levels #90
metadata.description:
The harmonic aspect of the composition is based on the application of various scales and chords - often derived from a central tonality - that are layered and interleaved in a manner similar to the visual shapes of the piece. This creates a constantly shifting harmonic landscape that is both familiar and unpredictable.

The rhythmic element of the composition is based on the layering of multiple polyrhythms, creating a complex and ever-shifting pulse. The polyrhythms are often based on a central pulse that is then layered and interleaved with other polyrhythms to create a complex and dynamic rhythmical landscape.

Overall, the pieces are designed to explore the relationships between shapes, harmonies, and rhythms in a way that is both logical and unexpected. The goal is to create a composition that is both cohesive and unpredictable, allowing for an ever-evolving soundscape of sound and movement.

press s to save png

metadata.name: Less is More #20
metadata.description:
In this case, we tried to avoid abstract expressionist tendencies by removing personal scenarios.
Take a step back and let's create a geometrical work that intentionally avoids the usual conventional elements, focusing mainly on logic and physics concepts such as mathematical expansions and gravity.
In fact, we based our work and expression on the basis of simplicity and simple methods, as well as free from the usual philosophical or pseudo-philosophical complexity, and we concluded that by using simple geometric shapes, color, form, and material can be achieved in a pure manner.
Made by p5.js
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #73
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to ‚Äúlush, green‚Äù and Brut means ‚Äúdry, raw, or unrefined.‚Äù

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth‚Ä¶ but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-BorgstroÃàm, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

metadata.name: WHISPERS (in code) #124
metadata.description:
WHISPERS (in code) is part of the fx(hash) interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022.‚Ä®
The project is a collaborative performance between the viewer and AI. It reverses the usual approach of using AI as a tool to perform our intents (as in popular prompt-based AI methods) and gives the decision-making power to the AI, where we, humans, receive instructions on how to proceed in the creative process. Interaction happens in a multi-stage manner, in a metaphor for the process of training neural networks. At each step, after the user performs the action, they can send the image for evaluation by the neural network and receive another instruction (similarly to how networks learn by receiving feedback from the loss function).¬†¬†What makes us different from the machines, however, is the presence of free will, and our ability to disobey the machine‚Äôs guidance. We are not restricted to its instructions and are free to interact with and break the artwork.‚Ä®

Artwork is built on layers of photography, AI, GAN, diffusion, classification convolutional networks, random pixel manipulations, and user interaction. Like with most artist projects, it starts with a few memories, that are then re-imagined by GAN. The initial building blocks are a combination of photographs and AI outputs. The apparent lack of coherent subject choice in input images signifies how we build the perception of the world around us and apply an individual hierarchy to elements worth remembering. The blocks are then stripped of meaning by reducing them to abstract shapes and applying stochastic image transformations, guided by randomness. The neural network then learns to classify the images and outputs its best guesses on how to improve the pictures.¬†
‚Ä®
The goal of the project is to explore the controversial question of authorship through the use of tools incorporating AI. Does it lie with decisive or executive power? Here, the boundaries are blurred and one can no longer distinguish the clear author of a finished artwork - is it the artist, AI, serendipity, or viewer?¬†


- Use your mouse to perform machine instructions.
- Use the "E" key to ask the neural network for instructions.
- Use the "R" key to reset the drawing.
- Use the "S" key to export an image.

metadata.name: Tangentum #120
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400
